children.text: Introduction
According to
InternetLiveStats

, 5.5 Billion people are connected to the internet and surprisingly this count is increasing every second as we talk about it. Also, there are almost 2 billion websites all over the world on the internet and almost 175 new websites are created every minute! In addition to this, at least a million laptops, tablets, and mobile phones are being sold every day throughout the world.

With the advancements in technology and easy access to the internet, most people are connected to the internet throughout the day and visit many websites and applications. As per a survey, 88% of mobile time is spent on apps.
You heard it right!
As mobile app usage grows in popularity, the number of app downloads worldwide increases as well.
Have you ever wondered how these apps are built?
Fun Fact
Understanding the data flow
Let's try to understand the fundamentals first. We are all connected to the internet.
The
internet
is the network of computers, or servers, communicating with one another by sending and receiving data. The original "Internet" was established in 1969, called
ARPANET

, which connected computers between various institutions. Today, many more cables and server hardware connect all the computers on the internet. The lines between the dots in the image below represent how the world is interconnected today enabling us to share and access the data.
Each of these dots you can think of as a server, but a certain type of server, namely known as a
router

. And a router, as the name implies, just routes data left to right, top to bottom, from one point to another. Therefore, routers are specialized computers, with CPUs and memory, that route, or relay, data from one point to another. 

For example, we might have routers that accept data and send them out from one point to another, in your home/on campus/in a coffee shop where we have internet access.

Your laptop or phone knows when it boots up at the beginning of the day, what the local router is, and what the address of that local router is. So if you want to send an email from your laptop, It is essentially going to hand it to the nearest IIITHyderabad router. And from there, it goes on to another nearest router and then to another, and so on, until finally, it reaches CMU’s email server.

So we need the Internet to establish connections between multiple devices and routes to route our data to the right destination. Apart from these two, there are a few other things that are involved in the process of sending and receiving the data to the right destination.
All of our devices including routers, phones, and laptops speak something called
TCP/IP
, a set of acronyms that refers to two protocols, two conventions, that computers use to inter-communicate these days.
A
protocol
is like a set of rules, that you behave.  We follow protocols all the time. One classic example of a protocol nowadays is wearing a face mask.
So protocols are just a set of rules that we all follow and adhere to, somewhere standardized and documented.

Computers use protocols all the time to govern how they are sending information and receiving information. TCP and IP are two such protocols that standardize this as follows. In the real world, we might write an address on an envelope to send a letter to someone, along with our address for a letter in return. But computers on the internet have unique addresses of their own, known as
IP addresses
An example  IP address is 192.158.1.38.
An IP address is just a numeric identifier on the internet that allows computers to differentiate and identify various destination computers. Typically, the format of IP addresses
and must use 32 bits or 4 bytes. Each of the hash symbols is a number from 0 through 255. So, the full IP addressing range goes from 0.0.0.0 to 255.255.255.255.
This will give us around 4 billion unique IP addresses, but we know that there are more than 4 billion devices that are connected to the internet.
You are right! This is a problem because all devices should have their unique IP addresses.

To overcome this issue of limited IP addresses there's another type of IP address that's starting to be used more commonly. This is version 4 of IP. There's also version 6 which, instead of 32 bits, uses 128 bits, which gives us a crazy number of possible addresses for computers, so we can at least handle all of the additional devices we now have today.
But on the internet, you presumably know that there are not just email servers. There are web servers, chat servers, video servers, and game servers, as we do various things over the internet.
Now once the IIIT Hyderabad server receives an email from your laptop, how does it know that it is an email and not a webpage or a Skype call?

Recall the TCP/IP protocol. TCP, transmission control protocol, is a protocol for sending and receiving data. One of the features of TCP is, it allows for a single server, at the same IP address, to provide multiple services through the use of a port number, a small integer added to the IP address. So now it not only contains an IP address but also a port number that represents what kind of service is being sent from point A to point B, whether it's email, web traffic, Skype, or something else.
For example, HTTP is sent to port number 80, and HTTPS uses port number 443.
Know more about the port numbers
here
All the data will be shared in packets.
